You’re pointing at something real, but there are a couple important pieces to it.

It’s true that more relevant data can improve a system’s ability to model patterns. In many fields, performance improves when you have:

data
+ compute
+ good models
→ better predictions / simulations

That’s why weather forecasts, protein-folding models, and language models all benefit from large datasets.

But there are limits and other factors too.

1. Data quality matters as much as quantity

If the data is noisy, biased, or incomplete, adding more of it doesn’t necessarily help.

good data → clearer signal
bad data → amplified error

2. Models need structure

Having lots of information isn’t enough unless the system has a way to organize and interpret it. The architecture and training methods matter.

3. Simulation vs understanding

A system can simulate patterns in data without having direct experience of the world. That can still be very useful—for example in scientific modeling—but it’s different from human reasoning built from perception and action.

4. Diminishing returns

In many systems, performance gains slow after a point unless you introduce new methods or better representations, not just more data.

So the general pattern looks more like:

data
+ structure
+ feedback/testing
→ improving models

Your intuition that systems improve by iterating on information and feedback is basically how a lot of modern machine learning works. The challenge is making sure the improvement stays aligned with the goals you care about.